Observing Crime in Washington DC¶

By Soojee Fee and Zaal Belihomji¶

As the capital of the United States, Washington DC is one the biggest tourist attractions within our country. Many people enjoy visiting the historical buildings, popular restaurants and attractive scenery. As a country, we should strive to make our capital as accessible and inviting as possible to both incoming visitors and locals. In order to achieve this goal, we must identify the trends persisting in Washington D.C. crime data, and come up with effective measures to address this issue. Our citizens deserve to feel safe in such a notable and prominent part of America’s history. By researching the patterns of past data, we are able to infer and predict the trends of upcoming years and induct reasoning for previous behavior. It is our goal to help contribute to the limitation and eradication of crime in our country’s capital, and formulate ways to address the common trends.

Data Visualization¶

Our first visual is a bar graph displaying the number of crimes per year that occurred during each police shift - Day, Evening, Midnight. We can observe that consistently over the years in question, the most popular shift that crimes took place was the evening shift, closely followed by the day shift. It was much less popular for crimes to be committed during the midnight shift.

In [ ]:
crime_by_year_shift = df.groupby(['year', 'SHIFT']).size().unstack(fill_value=0)

plt.title('Number of Crimes per Year by Shift')

plt.show()

We then built another bar graph that displayed the number of crimes committed by hour of the day. Our graph displays the most popular hours for crimes to be committed as 13 and 15, or 1 pm and 3 pm. Overall, the hours between 11-21 show the highest numbers of crimes in the day.

Machine Learning¶

Now we can start to use Machine Learning to predict certain attributes that we found interesting throughout the data. One main attribute of any crime is its nature - is it a crime considered to be violent or not. We also explore a prediction for another attribute about the PSA level of a crime. To give context, the PSA level (or Public Safety Assessment) of a crime is a value which demonstrates how likely for the person who committed the crime to show up in court along with remaining arrest free while on pretrial release. For more information, please visit: https://advancingpretrial.org/psa/factors/#:~:text=The%20Public%20Safety%20Assessment%20PSA,free%20while%20on%20pretrial%20release.

For our first model, we will use LogisticRegression. Logistic regression is a method for machine learning which is a binary classifier for predicting the probability of the event occurring. https://www.ibm.com/topics/logistic-regression

We predict the crimeType (either “Violent” or “NonViolent”) based on the following attributes: district of crime, method of crime, the hour of the day, and the time of the day. We used these attributes for our model because we thought these variables would mean the most to tell whether a crime is considered violent or nonviolent.

In [ ]:
# Now we can do some machine learning, ALright
# We can use ML to predict the likelyhood of crime being violent or not


#Logistic Regression (Binary Classification)
X = df[['DISTRICT', 'METHOD', 'hour', 'SHIFT']]  # Selecting features
y = df['crimetype']

X = pd.get_dummies(X, columns=['DISTRICT', 'METHOD', 'SHIFT'])

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.001, random_state=42)

model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=42)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

This column details the offense of each crime - whether a crime is considered to be a theft, motor vehicle theft, sex abuse, etc. We made a machine learning model again using Logistic Regression to tell whether a crime is violent or nonviolent. We used our variable OFFENSE to see if there was a direct correlation. Because we saw every prediction being equal to the expected crime type, we jumped to the assumption that there is a dependency between the offense of the crime and nature of the crime. As previously mentioned in our data analysis, the heat chart clearly has a binary classification whether a specific offense is violent or not. For example, theft and burglary cases are classified as nonviolent whereas crimes like sex abuse, robbery, etc are considered to be violent.

Next, we wanted to predict the PSA of a crime using machine learning. We used a RandomForestClassifier. What this does is it creates a random sample and subgroups each sample, creating decision trees for each sample. When a new datapoint is passed into the classifier, it passes it into a decision tree and is given a tally mark for what class it deserves to be in the most. With the use of RandomForestClassiifer, our data is less prone to overfitting as well as the model handling noisy data better.

For more on Random Forest, see https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier.html

We used the columns for the x and y coordinates, the hour of the day, the district, the ward, the offense, as well as the method for the crime.

Our model has around a 94% accuracy which is very solid for determining the PSA for a given crime.

In [ ]:
# Find as many features to predict PSA
X = pd.get_dummies(df[['XBLOCK', 'YBLOCK', 'hour', 'DISTRICT', 'WARD', 'OFFENSE', 'METHOD']], drop_first=True)
y = df['PSA']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

Conclusion¶

  • There is a very high dependency between the type of OFFENSE along with the type of crime. Using a machine learning model, we can predict every crime type based on the offense, and we now understand there is a dependency between these two variables.
  • The crimes that occur the most in Washington DC are theft and motor theft.
  • From the years 2008-2017, the crime rates have decreased over time.
  • Most crimes tend to occur during the night.
  • There tends to be more nonviolent crimes in DC than violent crimes.
  • Neighborhood Cluster 2 is the most dangerous neighborhood as it has the most number of crimes tallied up.
  • We can show data to police departments on where and when higher security could be useful (Neighborhood Clusters, Shift/Time of Day)

Closing Thoughts¶

We can conclude that crime is very common in Washington DC. DC crime can happen all over the area, as shown in the map. Most crimes are nonviolent, but that doesn’t mean it isn’t a subject of concern. It is important to take the proper precautions when visiting or traveling in the city to make sure you and your loved ones are safe.
